item.title: Alex Pretti, was my nurse at the Minneapolis va
item.description: I've mentioned this in some comments, but it deserves its own attention. I'm a veteran of the U.S. Navy. I started using the Minneapolis VA in 2020. I have a pretty significant phobia of needles. I have fainted more than once, and get tunnel vision on just about every injection or blood draw that happens because of them. Alex was a great nurse to me, probably in my 16 years of using the VA, one of the most kind, chill, and unjudgmental nurses I have had, and I have had a lot. He made what has always been an anxiety causing experience for me, manageable. he waited on me patiently, gave me the extra time i needed to unpsych myself, and proceeded as if everything was perfectly normal. He conducted himself, in a way every single nurse should strive to achieve in my opinion. In a single interaction he cemented his existence in my memory. The VA and all veterans have lost a great human being serving them. I encourage all veterans, especially those in Minneapolis, to use your blue button health report and see if he treated you, recall your experience with him, and share it. The Minneapolis VA sees over 100k veterans a year, chances are you probably saw him if you use them. Alex is not just some face, some martyr murdered by ICE, he is a human being, who had real, long lasting impact in his community, and we are less for not having him with us any more. Fuck ICE.
